{"type":"message","id":"1e4e68c4","parentId":"b89a0ad3","timestamp":"2026-05-26T07:53:36.468Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So the table name is `TbHeroSkin`. My script should match on `HeroSkin` or `TbHeroSkin`. Let me check what the issue is. The findTableDef function was looking `tableName.replace(/^Tb/i, '').toLowerCase()`. \n\nSo when I input \"HeroSkin\", it should match `TbHeroSkin` → `heroskin` after stripping `Tb`. Let me check if the function is handling the data correctly. \n\nActually, looking at my code more carefully:\n\n```javascript\nconst def = rows.find(r => {\n    const name = String(r[0] || '').trim();\n    const fullName = String(r[1] || '');\n    return name.replace(/^Tb/i, '').toLowerCase() === normalized\n        || name.toLowerCase() === tableName.toLowerCase()\n        || fullName.replace(/Config$/i, '').toLowerCase() === normalized;\n});\n```\n\nWait, the input is \"HeroSkin\" which becomes `normalized = 'heroskin'`.\n\nThen comparing against:\n- `name = 'TbHeroSkin'` → `name.replace(/^Tb/i, '').toLowerCase()` = `heroskin` ✅ should match!\n\nBut the issue might be in how the CSV rows are parsed. The first column in the CSV output shows `,TbHeroSkin` but the actual xlsx cell might be different. Let me check - the xlsx2csv output had:\n`,TbSkin,SkinConfig,TRUE,Skin.xlsx,,,`\n`,TbHeroSkin,HeroSkinConfig,TRUE,HeroSkin.xlsx,,,,`\n\nWait, column 0 in those rows: `TbHeroSkin` - but in my script, I was checking `r[0]`. The issue might be in how sheet_to_json works with horizontal rows. Let me debug this.\n\nActually, the first column of the xlsx might be different than what I expect. Let me look at the output from the script. The `--help` output shows `→ HeroSkin.xlsx` without the table name prefix, meaning the table name column might be empty or have a dot prefix.\n\nActually, looking at the xlsx2csv output for `__tables__.xlsx`:\n\n```\n##var,full_name,value_type,read_schema_from_file,input,index,mode,group,comment,tags,output\n,,,false时取已有定义，true为从excel标题头和属性栏读取定义,...\n,TbCommon,CommonConfig,TRUE,Common.xlsx,,,\n,TbCard,CardConfig,TRUE,Card.xlsx,,,\n```\n\nSo column 0 (##var) has values like `TbCommon`, `TbCard`, etc. And column 1 (full_name) has `CommonConfig`, `CardConfig`, etc.\n\nIn my script, I look at `r[0]` which is the first column (##var), and `r[1]` which is full_name. \n\nWait - my script uses `r[0]` for the first column. But sheet_to_json with `{header: 1}` returns an array where `r[0]` is the first column. Let me trace through:\n\nFor the row `,TbHeroSkin,HeroSkinConfig,TRUE,HeroSkin.xlsx,,,,`:\n- r[0] = empty string? Or \"TbHeroSkin\"?\n\nLooking at the CSV output, the first character is `,` which might mean the first column is empty. Let me check with the xlsx more carefully.\n\nActually the first row shows:\n```\n##var,full_name,value_type,read_schema_from_file,input,index,mode,group,comment,tags,output\n```\nSo column 0 = ##var header, and when we see `,TbHeroSkin`, that means r[0] might be empty here.\n\nHmm, but the data row `,TbHeroSkin,HeroSkinConfig...` has an empty first column. So in the xlsx, the ##var column is empty for data rows, and the actual table name TbHeroSkin might be in a different column.\n\nWait, looking at the first data row: `,TbCommon,CommonConfig,TRUE,Common.xlsx,,,,,,`\n\nThis means:\n- r[0] = \"\" (empty)\n- r[1] = \"TbCommon\" \n- r[2] = \"CommonConfig\"\n- etc.\n\nSo the ##var column (r[0]) is EMPTY for data rows! The actual table name is in r[1] (full_name column header).\n\nThis means my script's search is wrong - I was searching r[0] but the data is in r[1]. Let me fix the script.\n\nActually look again at the first row:\n```\n##var,full_name,value_type,read_schema_from_file,input,index,mode,group,comment,tags,output\n```\n\nAnd then: `,TbCommon,CommonConfig,TRUE,Common.xlsx,,,,,,`\n\nSo in the xlsx:\n- The first row has ##var in cell A1\n- But the data rows have the ##var column (A) EMPTY\n- The actual table name (TbCommon) is in column B (full_name)\n\nWait, but my listTables() function works and shows `TbHeroSkin → HeroSkin.xlsx`. So the data IS available somewhere. Let me re-examine.\n\nActually looking at the first data row: `,TbCommon,CommonConfig,TRUE,...`\nThis in CSV format with the first column being empty:\n- Column 0 (A): empty\n- Column 1 (B): TbCommon\n- Column 2 (C): CommonConfig\n- Column 3 (D): TRUE\n- Column 4 (E): Common.xlsx\n\nSo in my sheet_to_json with header:1, r[0] = \"\", r[1] = \"TbCommon\", r[2] = \"CommonConfig\", r[3] = \"TRUE\", r[4] = \"Common.xlsx\"\n\nMy script was checking `r[0]` which is empty, so it couldn't find the match by r[0] which starts with 'Tb'. My listTables() function was checking `r[1]` which has the actual table name. So let me fix the script to use r[1] for the table name.\n\nWait actually, let me re-check the test output `node add_field.mjs --help`. It showed:\n```\n                            → Common.xlsx          \n```\nThe table name on the left is blank. This confirms r[0] is empty for data rows. The code `listTables` uses `r[1]` which starts with 'Tb'. But the output doesn't show it because the tableRows were filtered by `r[1] && r[1].startsWith('Tb')`. Wait, the output shows blank spaces before the arrow. So the padEnd is working on an empty string.\n\nHmm, let me look at this:\n\n```javascript\nconst tableRows = rows.filter(r => r[1] && r[1].startsWith('Tb'));\nreturn tableRows.map(r => {\n    const name = String(r[0] || '').padEnd(25);  // r[0] is empty\n```\n\nSo r[0] is empty string, but r[1] has the table name. I need to fix the script to use r[1] as the name.\n\nLet me fix both findTableDef and listTables to use r[1] instead of r[0].","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"问题找到了 — `__tables__.xlsx` 中表名在第二列（r[1]），脚本搜索的是第一列。让我修一下。"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_n28MNjtCTrx5ISUIuJYc6922","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\plugin-skills\\solo-config-fiel